we should probably continue to support string based icon types. this isn't preferred since it can cause challenges with code splitting but in some cases it's driven by our backend so it has to be serialized.
you probably want something like this:
```ts
type FormattedIconProps =
 | { icon: IconType | IconType_deprecated; imgSrc?: never; size?: IconSize; className?: string }
 | { icon?: never; imgSrc: string; size?: IconSize; className?: string };
```

I'm not sure I understand why a discriminated union wouldn't work here too, it could be something like this:
```ts
type FormattedIconCommon = {
 size?: IconSize;
 className?: string;
};

type FormattedIconProps =
 | (FormattedIconCommon & {
 kind: 'icon';
 icon: IconType | IconType_deprecated;
 })
 | (FormattedIconCommon & {
 kind: 'img';
 imgSrc: string;
 });

```

and then you can use convertToGlazeIconType on `icon` to normalize between string or component representation

I know we're aliasing the string version of `IconType` to _deprecated in a bunch of spots but I'm not sure that actually is accurate anymore.

